I doubt not but the Adverb (olùm) is to be undertood; 'tis not your Valour only that gives me this concernment; but I find alo, by this portent, that Jupiter is my Enemy. For Turnus fled before, when his firt Sword was broken, 'till his Siter upply'd him with a better; which indeed he cou'd not ue; becaue Aeneas kept him at a ditance with his Spear. I wonder Ruaeus aw not this, where he charges his Author o unjutly, for giving Turnus a econd Sword, to


no purpoe. How cou'd he faten a blow, or make a thrut, when he was not uffer'd to approach? Beides, the chief Errand of the Dira, was to warn Juturna from the Field, for he cou'd have brought the Chariot again, when he aw her Brother worted in the Duel. I might farther add, that Aeneas was o eager of the Fight, that he left the City, now almot in his Poeion, to decide his quarrel with Turnus by the Sword: Whereas Turnus had manifetly declin'd the Combate, and uffer'd his Siter to convey him as far from the reach of his Enemy as he cou'd. I ay not only uffer'd her, but conented to it; for 'tis plain, he knew her by thee words;


O oror, & dudum agnovi, cùm prima per artem,

Faedera turbati, teque haec in bella dediti;

Et nunc nequicquam fallis Dea.—

I have omitted the Four Preliminary Lines of the Firt Aeneid: Becaue I think them inferiour to any Four others, in the whole Poem: and conequently, believe they are not Virgil's. There is too great a gap betwixt the Adjective vicina in the Second Line, and the Subtantive Arva in the latter end of the Third, which keeps his meaning in obcurity too long: And is contrary to the clearnes of his Style.
t quamvis avidis Is too ambitious an Ornament to be his, and Gratum opus Agricolis, Are all words unneceary, and Independent of what he had aid before. Horrentia Martis Arma, Is wore than any of the ret. Horrentia is uch a flat Epithete, as Tully wou'd have given us in his Veres. 'Tis a meer filler; to top a vacancy in the Hexameter, and connect the Preface to the Work of Virgil. Our Author eems to ound a Charge, and begins like the clangour of a Trumpet;
Arma, virumque cano; Trojae qui primus ab oris.

Line 1140. 


                           Embrace again, my Sons; be Foes no more;



                           Nor tain your Country with her Childrens gore:



                           And thou the firt, lay down thy lawles claim;



                           Thou of my Blood, who bear't the Julian Name.

Line, 1236, and 1237.


Two Gates the ilent Houe of Sleep adorn;

Of polih'd Iv'ry this; that of tranparent Horn.

                     Virgil borrow'd this Imagination from Homer, Odyes the 19th. Line 562. The Tranlation gives the reaon, why true Prophetic Dreams are aid to pas through the Gate of Horn, by adding the Epithete tranparent: Which is not in Virgil; whoe Words are only thee;


Sunt geminae Somni portae; quarum altera fertur

Cornea—

The Tranlation is infinitely hort of Virgil, whoe Words are thee;



                           —Tibi enim, tibi maxima Juno



                           Mactat acra ferens, & cum grege itit ad aram.

